{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use British English|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox writer | name = Anne-Marie Casey | image = | imagesize = | caption = | pseudonym = Anne-Marie Casey | birth_date = 7 July 1965 | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Writer | nationality = British, Irish | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | magnum_opus = | influences = | influenced = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Anne-Marie Casey''' (born 7 July 1965) was a [[Prime time|primetime]] TV screenwriter and producer before moving into stage adaptation and novels.
==Biography== Casey was born in 1965 in the UK to an Irish father. She was educated in [[St Bernard's Catholic Grammar School|St Bernard's convent school]] before going to college in [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] where she studied English and then [[Syracuse University]], New York where she studied Film and TV. She became a producer and script editor with her TV shows in the primetime slot. She married writer [[Joseph O'Connor]] with whom she had two sons and moved to [[Killiney]], [[County Dublin|Co Dublin]]. There she began working on scripts for [[Raidió Teilifís Éireann|RTÉ]]. The next step was when she began to create scripts for the stage, in 2011 she created the stage adaptation of [[Louisa May Alcott]]'s classic novel [[Little Women]]. In 2014 she adapted [[Wuthering Heights]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/artsfilmtv/books/beginners-pluck--anne-marie-casey-232991.html|title=Anne-Marie Casey|author=Sue Leonard}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishplayography.com/person.aspx?personid=17238|title=Irish Plays}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/ireland/article1486120.ece|title=The Sunday Times}}</ref>
During this time Casey also began to write novels. Her first came out in 2013 and was a [[Kirkus Reviews]] best book of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/anne-marie-casey/no-one-could-have-guessed-the-weather/|title=Kirkus Reviews}}</ref>
