'''Baileo''' is a custom house,<ref name=baileo>{{cite web|author= |url=http://worlduniquees.blogspot.com/2014/01/baileo-house-traditional-house-maluku.html |title=Baileo House, Traditional House Maluku from Indonesian &#124; Unique, Exotic, Funny and More |publisher=Worlduniquees.blogspot.com |date=21 January 2014 |accessdate=2016-05-01}}</ref> in [[Maluku (province)|Maluku]] and [[North Maluku]], [[Indonesia]].<ref name="Kebudayaan Indonesia">{{cite web| url=http://kebudayaanindonesia.net/id/culture/1031/rumah-baileo| title= ''Rumah Baileo''| publisher= KebudayaanIndonesia.net| accessdate= 16 May 2014}}</ref> The term is derived from the word ''bale'' or ''balai'', which is a [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]] word for a village meeting place.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Nuaulu Religious Practices: The Frequency and Reproduction of Rituals in Moluccan Society|last=Ellen|first=Roy|publisher=KITLV Press|year=2012|isbn=9789067183918|location=Leiden|pages=226}}</ref>  The house is a representation of the Baileo [[Maluku culture]] and has an important function in the life of the community<ref name="Kebudayaan Indonesia" /> that is why the structure forms part of the identity of any community in the [[Moluccas]]. There are instances where the baileo serves as a [[mosque]] or [[Church (building)|church]]<ref name="Slide Share">{{cite web|url= http://www.slideshare.net/guest7ca33fa/rumah-adat-maluku| title= ''Rumah Adat Maluku (Baileo)''| publisher= Slideshare.net| accessdate= 17 May 2014}}</ref> or adjacent to one.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Communities and Conservation: Histories and Politics of Community-Based Natural Resource Management|last=Brosius|first=Peter|last2=Tsing|first2=Anna|last3=Zerner|first3=Charles|publisher=Rowman Altamira Press|year=2005|isbn=0759105057|location=Lanham, MD|pages=381}}</ref> This is the case when the house serves as a repository for sacred objects<ref name="baileo" /> and a place of [[Ceremony|traditional ceremonies]]<ref name="baileo" /> in addition to its function as a place for community meetings.<ref name="Slide Share" /> 

The ''baileo,'' which is present in every Moluccan village, is usually a village landmark with its open architecture.<ref name=":1" /> It also has a large size and unique appearance when compared to other buildings in its vicinity.<ref name="AnneAhira">{{cite web| url= http://www.anneahira.com/rumah-adat-maluku.htm| title= ''Mengenal Rumah Adat Maluku''| publisher= Anneahira.com| accessdate= 17 May 2014}}</ref><ref name="Alfarish">[https://web.archive.org/web/20151216221029/http://www.toyotareferences.com/2015/09/2017-toyota-celica-specs-and-release.html]</ref> It is traditionally built from local materials such as planked timber, cement, stone or brick with wood shingle, and thatch or zinc roof.<ref name=":0" />

Recent interest in baileo emerged within the recent revival process in parts of Indonesia that seeks to reestablish traditional institutions and symbols.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Journal of Legal Pluralism and Unofficial Law 62/2010|last=Wiber|first=Melanie|last2=Woodman|first2=Gordon|publisher=LIT Verlag Munster|year=2010|isbn=9783643998958|location=Munster|pages=19}}</ref>
